{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280605311/1949030601/0112.xml":{"full_text":"Hungary Charges Plot\nBy Vatican to Unite\nAll Danubian Nations\n(Continued From First Page.i\nwere drawn from them by police\nintimidation.\nPresiding Judge Pal Biro called\nthe repudiation by Georgy Nagy,\na broker, \u201can attempt to influ\nence court room spectators\u201d and\nsentenced him to three years in\nJail.\nIn rejecting repudiations by\nZsigmond Deutsch, a broker, and\nthe four others. Judge Biro said\nthe evidence showed their pre\ntrial confessions \u201ccould not be the\nInventions of police authorities.\u201d\nMr. Deutsch, who pleaded that1\nhe had confessed and implicated\nfour innocent persons only be\ncause he was held in solitary con-;\nflnement. was sentenced to four\nyears.\nOther Sentences.\nThe other four who repudiated,\nand their sentences, are:\nEde Dukesz and Victor Dukesz,\nthree years and $5,250 fine each;\nPal Csonka, three and a half years\nand $2,125 fine, and Mrs. Jozsef\nPorgacs. 18 months and $83 fine.\nOther sentences were:\nThe Rev. Jozsef Zid, treasurer\nof the Jesuit order in Hungary,\nand the Jesuit Brother Janos Za\nradi, three years in Jail each, and\nnine years\u2019 loss of political rights.\nKaroly Polde6. a broker, four\nyears\u2019 imprisonment.\nDezso Tolnai, a banker, two\nyears\u2019 imprisonment and $1,250\nfine.\nGabor Vajkal, a banker, one\nyear in jail and $1,830 fine.\nUnder Hungarian law. the sen\ntence of a Workers\u2019 Court may\nnot be appealed. Cardinal Minds\nsenty was convicted by a People's\nCourt, from which appeal is per\nmitted. The cardinal seeks a re\nduction of sentence, and the prose\ncution has countered with an ap\npeal that the sentence of life im\nprisonment was not heavy enough.\nThe number of defendants had\nbeen reduced by illness from 15\nto 14. and then 13. Trials of\nDivadar Wydler, a banker, and\n8andor Foldes, a broker, will be\nheld later.\nCharge Made to Party Leader*.\nDeputy Premier Rakosi made his\neharge against the Vatican at a\nmeeting of leaders of the Hun\ngarian Workers (Communist and\nSocialist) Party, of which he Is\n\u25a0ecretary-general.\nHe spoke of the case of Car\ndinal Mindszenty, the Hungarian\nfive-year plan and problems of\nthe party and the government. Re\nferring to the alleged plan for a\n\"Danubian monarchy,\u201d he said\nthe United States permitted Arch\nduke Otto Hapsburg, pretender to\nthe nonexistent Austro-Hungarian\nthrone, to form an Austrian legion\nIn 1942.\n\"The majority of Catholic\nbishops do not like Hungarian\ndemocracy,\u201d Rakosi said. \"But the\nfact they were inclined to conclude\nan economic agreement with the\ngovernment three days after\nMindszenty's arrest and 10 days\nlater commenced talks concern\ning church-state relations proved\nthey were fully aware that there\nis no question of persecution of\nreligion.\u201d\nThe Vatican interfered, he said,\nand disapproved of further talks.\nHe said that otherwise they could\nhave ended in success.\nHe said the Hungarian people\n(65 per cent Catholics) \"were\npleased by the arrest and trial of\nMindszenty.\u201d\nReligion Declared Free.\nPacts concluded with all\nchurches except the Roman\nCatholic Church, he said, have\n\u201cprovided more freedom of reli\ngion than is reserved by England,\nAmerica or any other bourgeois\ncountry.\u201d\nSpeaking of political affairs,\nRakosi said about 170,000 mem\nbers were excluded from his own\nparty after a recent \u201crevision\u201d\nand the party will now have less\nthan 1,000,000 members.\n\"But the qaulity will be much\nbetter,\u201d he added.\nFactory hands came in for\npraise, but Rakosi said at least\n300,000 new workers are needed\nby industry to increase the na\ntional income by 60 per cent under\nthe new five-year plan. He prom\nised telephone connections with\nevery village.\nVatican Source Said Rakosi\nSought Catholic Agreement\nVATICAN CITY, Mar. 5 UP).\u2014\nAn informed Vatican source said\ntoday that Matyas Rakosi, Com\nmunist Hungarian deputy premier,\nhad recently sought an agreement\nwith the Council of Catholic\nBishops in Hungary.\nThe informant said the agree\nment did not materialize because\nRakosi wanted the bishops to sign\na statement, prior to any discus\nsions. saying the \u201cCatholic Church\nis not persecuted in Hungary.\u201d\nThe Vatican source said Arch\nbishop Giulio Czapik of Eger, dean\nof Hungary\u2019s Catholic bishops, had\ntold Rakosi the bishops were will\ning to issue a public statement\nmaking clear that the \u201cchurches\nwere open to worship and the\nfaithful were not forbidden to take\nthe sacraments but that Catholic\nschools and institutions had been\nnationalized and therefore pure\nreligion was not possible for Cath\nolics in Hungary.\u201d\nThe informant said Rakosi was\nreported to have snapped back at\nMsgr. Czapik:\n\u201cIf you were replacing \u00bbJosef*\nCardinal Mindszenty, things would\nbe even worse between the church\nand the Hungarian state.\"\nFour Crash Survivors\nReturned by Russians\nBy the Associated Press\nBERLIN. Mar. 5.\u2014Four survi\nvors of the crash of an American\nairlift Skymaster in the Soviet\nrone of Germany were turned over\nto American authorities tonight.\nThe plane crashed last night\nBear Langensalza, killing one of\nthe crew. The four survivors para\nchuted.\nText of Truman Proposal for Revising Unification Act\nty the Associated Prass\nFollowing is the text of Presi\ndent Truman\u2019s message to Con\ngress yesterday on revision of the\nArmed Services Unification Act:\nThe maintenance of adequate\narmed force* ha* been one of the;\nprincipal functions of the Federal:\nGovernment since the establish-\nment of this Nation. Today we,\nmaintain our armed forces in sup- j\nport of our primary desire for j\nworld peace. They are evidence\nof our determination to devote ourj\nutmost efforts toward achieving that\nall-important goal.\nThroughout our history, the steady\nadvance of science and technology\nhas resulted in constant changes in\nthe means of warfare and the\ncharacted'of our armed forces. In\nthe few years since the cessation\nof hostilities in World War II, tre-;\nmendous developments in technology\nhave been made. The speed of air\ncraft ha* doubled, the means of\nundersea warfare have been rev\nolutionized, the range and accuracy\nof guided missiles have increased,\nthe potentialities of the atom have\nbeen more fully revealed.\nThe development of man's ability\nto shrink space and time and to\ncontrol natural forces makes im\nperative a corresponding develop\nment of the means for directing\nand controlling these new powers.\nThe effective and workable organ\nization of our Government, and'es\npecially of our armed forces, is\nessential in the modern world.\nThe recent reports of the Com\nmission of Organization of the Ex\necutive Branch of the Government\nhave focused attention on the im\nportance of the sound organization\n!of the Federal Government. The\ncommission has stated that the first\nessential to the achievement of\nbetter government is a general clari\nfication of the lines of authority and\nresponsibility within the Executive\nBranch. In its report entitled \"Na\ntional Security Organization,\u201d the\ncommission has specifically applied\nthis principle to the organization\nof our armed forces.\nCivilian Control Inadequate.\nThe report states that we now\nlack adequate civilian authority and,\ncontrol over the military forces, that\nmaximum efficiency and economy Is\nnot being realized in defense ex\npenditures, and that interservice j\nrelationships must be Improved to\nachieve the meet effective defense.\nThe recommendations of the com-;\nmission which would strengthen the,\nNational Military Establishment and\nthe position of the Secretary of De\nfense have great merit and present\nan objective toward which I believe\nwe must continue to move.\nI have long been aware of the\nnecessity for keeping our national\nsecurity organization abreast of our\nsecurity requirements. To this end,\nI recommend unification of the\narmed forces to the Congress in\nDecember 1945. My desire was to\nimprove our defense organization\nwhile the lessons of World War II\nwere still fresh in the minds of all.\nWe must not forget these lessons\nin evaluating our security position\ntoday.\nA great deal was learned from\nthose four years of war. We learned,\namong other things, that the or\nganization of our War and Navy\nDepartments, prescribed by detailed\nstatutes, was far too rigid and in\nflexible Ifor the actual conduct of\nwar. We learned that modem war\nrequired the combined use of air,\n.naval and land forces welded to\ngether under unified commands\n1 overseas, and under the strategic\ndirection of the Joint Chiefs of\nStaff.\nOther lessons were also learned.\nWe learned that widely diverse aup\nplv policies of the separate services\nwere costlv, and hampered the total\neffectiveness of military operations.\nWe learned that there were great\ndifferences in training and combat\ndoctrine among the services and\nthat these differences often pro\nvoked sharp conflicts in our thea\nters of operation.\nPlan Had Double Purpose.\nMy message to the Congress of\nDecember 1945 had a double pur\npose. It was Intended to take ad\nvantage of our wartime experience\nand to prevent a return to the out\nmoded forms of organization which\nexisted at the outbreak of the war.\nFollowing that message, the sub\nject of the proper organization of\nour armed forces was debated\nthroughout the Nation. After the\nmost careful consideration, the Na\ntional Security Act was enacted by\nthe Congress in July 1947.\nThis act has provided a practical\nand workable basis for beginning the\nunification of the military services\nand for co-ordinating military pol\nicy with foreign and economic pol\nicy. A few examples of the progress\nachieved in the period since the act\nbecame effective are evidence of its\nvalue.\nThe efficiency of military purchas\ning has steadily increased until to\nday more than 75 per cent of the\nmateriel of the armed services is\nprocured under co-ordinated pur-,\nchasing arrangements.\nA number of Joint training and\neducation programs have been in\nstituted so that the personnel of\neach service may gain a greater\nunderstanding of the weapons and\ndoctrine of the other services.\nMilitary Justice Revised.\nA uniform code of military jus-1\ntice has been developed, designed to\nbe applicable to the personnel of\nall the armed forces. This code is\nnow before the Congress for its\nconsideration.\nThe co-ordination of military\npolicy with foreign and economic i\npolicies has been greatly improved,\nprincipally through the efforts of\nthe National Security Council and\n1 the National Security Resources\nBoard.\nThe past 18 months have dispelled\n!any doubt that unification of the\narmed forces can yield great ad\nvantages to the Nation. No one\nj advocates a return to the outmoded\norganization of the days preceding!\nthe National Security Act. On the\ncontrady, the issue today is not\nwhether we should have unification,\nbut how we can make it more effec\ntive.\nWe have now had sufficient ex\nperience under the act to be able\nto identify and correct its weak\nnesses, without impairing the ad\nvantages we have obtained from\nits strength. We have also had the\nadvantage of a thoroughgoing ap\npraisal by the Commission on the\nOrganization of the Executive\nBranch of the Government. On the\nbasis of our experience to date, as\nfurther borne out by the commis\nsion, we should now proceed to make\nthe needed improvements in the\nact.\nDuties Too Limited.\nThe duties and responsibilities of\nthe Secretary of Defense as now set\nforth in the act are of too limited\na character, and are restricted to\nspecified items. For example, the\nact expressly provides that all duties\nnot specifically conferred upon the\nSecretary of Defense are to remain\nvested in the Secretaries of the\nArmy, the Navy and the Air Force.\nWhile the Secretary of Defense, as\nthe head of the National Military\nEstablishment, out to be ultimately\naccountable, under the President,\nfor its administration, he is speci\nfically limited by this act in the\ndegree to which he may hold the\nmilitary departments responsible to\nhim.\nThe departmental secretaries are\nspecifically authorized to deal di\nrectly with higher authority. Fur\nthermore, many of the key respon\nsibilities of the Secretary of De\nfense have been assigned by this\nstatute. Not to the Secretary, but\nto boards and agencies which derive\nmuch of their authority from the\nmilitary departments themselves.\nIn short, the act fails to provide j\nfor a fully responsible official with\nauthority adequate to meet his re\nsponalbility, whom the President\nand the Congress can hold account\nable. The act falls to provide the\nbasis for an organisation and a staff\nadequate to achieve the most effec\ntive and informed civilian control.\nI, therefore, recommend that the\nNational Security Act be amended\nto accomplish two basic purposes:\nFirst, to convert the National Mili\ntary Establishment into an executive\ndepartment of the Government, to\nbe known as the Department of De\nfense; and, second, to provide the\nSecretary of Defense with appro\npriate responsibility and authority\nand with civilian and military as\nsistance adequate to fulfill his en\nlarged responsibility.\nUrges Clarification ef Duties.\nWithin the new Department of\nDefense, I recommend that the de\npartments of the Army, the Navy\nand the Air Force be designated as\nmilitary departments. The respon\nsibility of the Secretary of Defense\nfor exercising direction, authority,\nand control over the affairs of the\nUnification\n(Continued From First Page.l\nviser to the President and the\nDefense Secretary.\nPrompt Consideration Urged.\nMr. Truman urged \u2018\u2018prompt\nconsideration\u201d of his proposals\nand cited as reasons for urgent\nstrengthening of the defense set\nup. the development of long\nj range bombers, guided missiles\nand atomic bombs.\nIn general, Mr. Truman's re\ncommendation followed those of\nI the Hoover Commission on Gov\nernmental Reorganization which,\njhe said, \"have great merit and\npresent an \u2018objective to which I\nbelieve we must continue to\nmove.\u201d\nThe broad powers which Mr.\nBerlin\n(Continued From First Page.)\nuted by the Soviet news agency,\nsaid in part that the situation re\ngarding the restitution of Soviet\nproperty in the American occupa\ntion zone of Germany is \"com\npletely inadmissible.\u201d\nMarshal Sokolovsky stressed in\nhis letter that the Soviet Union\ngot back properties worth only\n80,000 marks in 1948 while other\nnations, mainly those of the West\nern bloc, had received properties\nworth 174,000.000 marks.\n\u201cThese facts show,\u201d the letter\nsaid, \"that such unsatisfactory\nresults were caused by efforts of\nAmerican authorities to prevent\nthe restitution of Soviet property\nlooted by the Nazis.\nThe letter claimed American\nauthorities in Germany have sab\notaged activities of the Soviet\nrestitution mission by not permit\nting the Russian mission to in\nspect German factories, archives,\nmuseums, and art galleries in its\nefforts to pin down Soviet prop-:\nerties there.\nThe communication said most of\nthe Soviet applications for return\nof Russian property have been\nturned down by American au- i\nthorlties under several pretenses,\neven in cases when the German;\nhad said Soviet property was in\ntheir hands.\nRed Constitution Ready.\nMeanwhile, Communists com\npleted drafting a constitution to\nserve for a \u201cGerman democratic\nrepublic\" in the Soviet aone of\nGermany.\nIt was announced today that\nthe German people's council,\nwhich the Communists have spon\nsored, will convene here March\n18 to approve the draft.\nThat will constitute an Eastern\nanswer to the constituent assem\nbly of Bonn, where German dele\ngates are putting the finishing\ntouches on a constitution for the\nWest German State.\nBoth documents bid for the sup\nport of all Germany. But each\nwill be effective only in its own\npart of the country so long as the\nEast-West split goes unrepaired.\nBonn Draft Assailed.\nCommunist leaders assailed the\nBonn draft constitution in their\nmeeting here, f tto Grotewohl, co\nchairman of the Communist-led\nSocialist Unity Party, said the\nCommunist draft was written \"in\nfree public discussions, without\nany influence by an occupying\npower.\nIn contrast, he charged the Bonn\ndraft is not a German document,\nbut one written on orders of the\nWestern occupying powers.\nThe Bonn assembly is now work\ning on changes proposed by Gen.\nClay, British Gen. Sir Brian Rob\nertson and French Gen. Pierre\nKoenig to strengthen states rights\nin the projected West German\nFederation.\nChilean Legislators\nTo Be Elected Today\nBy th\u00bb Associated Press\nSANTIAGO, Chile, Mar. 5.\u2014\nChile was calm tonight on the\neve of national elections for con\ngress. Chileans will elect 147 dep\nuties and 20 of 45 senators to\nmorrow.\nThis is the first general election\nduring the administration of Pres\nident Gabriel Gonzalez Videla.\nPredictions are that the govern\nment will continue its control of\nboth the Senate and the Chamber\nof Deputies.\nThe campaign which closed to\nday was peaceful.\nThe armed forces will control\nthe voting and the government\nhas repeated that it will guarantee\n\u201cabsolute fairness.\u2019\u2019\nThe election will be the first in\nwhich the Communist Party is\nbanned. The Communists support\nthe National Democratic Front\none of the opposition groups. This\nparty will offer 67 of the 400 can\ndidates for deputy seats, and thre\nof the 43 senatorial candidates.\nTruman asked would be given\nto the Incoming Defense Secre\ntary, Louis Johnson, whose ap\npointment was annoi iced Thurs\nday by Mr. Trums He is to\nsucceed James Forrt ,a1, who was\none of the first to complain about\ninadequate authority for the De\nfense Secretary. The recommen\ndations also follow generally the\nsame lines as those advocated by\nMr. Forrestal.\nNo Mention of Demotions,\ni The President\u2019s mesa it made no\nmention of one recommendation\nof the Hoover Commission\u2014that\nthe present civilian secretaries of\nthe armed forces be demoted to\nthe positions of under secretaries\nof defense for Army, Navy and\nAir Force.\nj The message did point up the\nj the fact that the d' jartmental\nsecretaries now are authorized to\ndeal directly with higher au\nthority when they disagree with\ndecisions of the defense chief. It\nalso mentioned that many of the\nkey responsibilities of the Defense\nSecretary were assigned by law,\nnot to the secretary, but to boards\nand agencies which derive much\nof their authority from the mili\ntary departments themselves.\nHe said he was \u201cnot recom\nmending the blanket transfer of\nall statutory authority applicable\u201d\nto the Army, Navy and Air Force\nto the Defense Secretary, nor any\nchanges in the statutory assign\nment of combatant functions of\nthe Services.\n\u201cI recommend, however, that\nthe secretaries of the Army, Navy\nand Air Force administer the re\nrespective \u201cmilitary departments\nunder the authority, direction and\ncontrol of the Secretary of De- j\nfense,\u201d he declared.\nThus Mr. Truman followed the\nrecommendations of both the\nHoover Commission and Mr. For\nrestal that the word \"general\u201d be\nremoved from the section of the\nunification act which deals with\nthe Defense Secretary\u2019s authority\nover the three services.\nAt the Pentagon, officials said\nthat legislation designed to carry\nout the President's recommenda\ntions was being prepared and\nwould be forwarded to Congress\nshortly.\nDepartment of Defense should be\nmade clear. Furthermore, the pres\nent limitations and restrictions\nwhich are in appropriate to his\nstatus as head of an executive de\npartment should be removed. The\nSecretary of Defense should be the\nsole representative of the Depart\nment of Defense on the National\nSecurity Council.\nI am not recommending the\nblanket transfer of all statutory\nauthority applicable to the depart\nments of the Army, the Navy and\nIthe Air Force to the Secretary of\nDefense. Neither am I recommend\ning any change in the statutory\nissignment of combatant functions\nj to the Army. Navy and Air Force.\nI recommend, however, that the\nj Secretaries of the Army, the Navy\nand the Air Force administer the\nrespective military departments\nj under the authority, direction and\ncontrol of the Secretary of Defense.\nTo meet these additional re\nsponsibilities, the Secretary of De\nfense needs strengthened civilian\nand military assistance. This can\nbe provided by the creation of new\nposts and by the conversion of\nexisting agencies of the National\nMilitary Establishment into staff\nunits for the Secretary. I recom- j\nmend that Congress provide an\nUndersecretary of Defense and\nthree Assistant Secretaries of De\nfense.\nThe duties now placed by statute\nin the Munitions Board and the\nResearch and Development Board\nshould be iecognlzed as responsibil\nities of the Secretary of Defense.\nThe act should be amended to make\npossible the flexible use of both of\nthese agencies, and of ihe Joint\nChiefs of Staff, as staff units for the\nSecretary of Defense.\nProposal an Joint Chiefs.\nPinally, I recommend that the\nCongress provide for a chairman of\nthe Joint Chiefs of Staff, to take\nprecedence over all other military\npersonnel, and to be the principal\nmilitary adviser to the President\nand the Secretary of Defense, and\nto perform such ether duties as\nthey may prescribe.\nIn my Judgment, these changes\nwijl make possible effective organi\nzation and management of the De\npartment of Defense. They will\nprovide a responsible official at its\nhead, with strengthened civilian\nand military assistance, to under-.\ntake the immense Job of aiding the\nPresident and the Congress in de\ntermining defense needs and in\nsupervising the administration of\nour defense activities,\nj These measures are essential to\ncontinued and accelerated progress\ntoward unification. I am convinced\n;that only through making steady\nprogress toward this goal can we\nbe assured of serving our major\nobjectives, the most effective or\nganization of our armed forces, a\nfull return on our defense dollar,\nand strengthened civilian control, j\nI urge the Congress to give prompt\nconsideration to these recommenda\ntions. From the standpoint of pres\nent and potential cost to the Nation,\nthere is no more important area in\nwhich to work for improved organi\nzation and operations. Action on\nthese recommendations will prove1\nbeneficial to the Congress, the Am\n?rican people, and the President by\nproviding better means of assuring\ndefense needs and admlnlsteriing\nthe defense program. We should\nseize this opportunity to strengthen\nour defense organization which is so\nvital to the security of this Nation\nand the peace of the world.\nNow your creams\ndTld lotlQfi\u00a7\nDorothy Gray\nPlunging Neckline Treatment\nTo give you the throat care you need for your new\nneckline-down-to-there clothes, the Dorothy Gray Salon\nhas created a special Plunging Neckline Treatment which\nyou can duplicate in your own home! Here are the prepa\nrations you use be sure to apply them way, way down!\nFOUNDATION\nIf you\u2019re under 30\nSalon Cold Cream,\n$1 to $1\nTexture Lotion,\n$1 to $3.75\nSpecial Dry-Skin\nMixture, $2.25 to $8\nFinisheen, $1\nIf you\u2019re over 30\nDry-Skin Cleanser,\n$1 to $4\nOrange Flower Skin\nLotion, $1 to $3.75\nCellogen Cream, $3.50 to $5\nThroat Cream, $2 to $4\nCellogen Lotion, $5\n(AH Prices Plus Tax)\nDorothy Gray\nO 1*4* ly BereAy Grty, llnrltt*\nRed Radio Broadcasts\nCommunist Leaders'\nThreats of Sabotage\nly *h\u00bb Auociatcd Prats\nLONDON. Mar. 6\u2014The Moscow\nradio tonight broadcast three\nseparate items totaling 1,000\nwords on threats by Communist\nparty members in three countries\nthat they will sabotage any war\nagainst Russia.\nEach left no doubt that the\nthreat is a \u201cstop-the-Atlantic\nI pact\u201d attempt.\nThe reports, in the mid-evening\nnews broadcast, heard here, came\nj from France, Finland and Austria.\nFinnish Leader Quoted.\nWille Pessi, general secretary\nof the Finnish Communist Party,\nwas quoted as saying:\n\u2018\u2018Our position is the same as\nthat of the Communists of other\ncountries. The aggressors must\nbe bridled even before their At\nlantic union and other military\nblocs have time to start a war.\u201d\nIf \u2018\u2018imperialists\u201d should attack\nRussia, Pessi said, the duty of all\nCommunists is to help \u201crout the:\naggressor or aggressors.\u201d\nFrom Vienna, the radio quoted\nthe Austrian Communist Party\nnewspaper Oesterreichische Volks\nstimme as complaining that the\norgan of the \u201cruling peoples party\nin Graz\u201d openly urges Austria to\njoin the Atlantic pact.\nThe Communist paper con\ntinued:\n\"But the Austrian workers will\nnot permit the transformation of\nAustria into a strong point of the\nwarmongers.\u201d\nFrench Situation Discussed.\nDiscussing the situation in\nFrance, Moscow radio's own com\nmentator Yermashev said: \"The\nFrench people are fully deter\nmined to struggle against the con\nversion of their country into a\nwar base of the Anglo-American\naggressors.\u201d\nIt was Maurice Thorez, French\nCommunist leader, who first openly,\nexpressed the new party line.\nThe French government retaliated\nwith a series of arrests of Com\nmunists on treason charges.\n\"The present inner political\nevents in France have a wide in\nternational significance,\u201d said Yer\nmashev. \u201cThe entire Democratic\nworld is following them.\u201d\nStalin Sees Delegates\nFrom Northern Korea\nB^ the Associated Presft\nLONDON, Mar. 5.\u2014The Moscow\nradio said in a broadcast heard\nhere that Prime Minister Stalin\ntoday received a visiting delega\ntion from North Korea.\nThe broadcast said the delega\ntion is visiting Moscow to\nstrengthen \"political, economic\nand cultural ties with the Soviet\nUnion.\u201d Northern Korea was oc\ncupied by the Russian armies and\nhas a Communist government.\nPresent at the talks In the\nKremlin was Andrei Y. Vishinsky\nin his new role of Soviet foreign\nminister, the broadcast said.\nMcGrath Backs 2 Sales Tax j\nTo Prevent District Deficit\n(Continued From First Page.'*\nalternative\u201d In the District\u2019s un\nbalanced financial straits.\nThe proposal of Senator John\nston, Democrat, of South Carolina,\na member of the District Com\njmittee, that the whole tax prob\nlem be solved by a boost of $25,\n000,000 in the Federal payment,\nChairman McGrath put down as\ni \u201cunattainable.\u201d\nj Under the presen J; circum\nstances there \"certainly\u201d should\nbe an increase in the Federal\npayment. Senator McGrath said.\nBut he made clear he did not\n1 believe Congress would put the\nj whole load on the Federal Gov\nernment.\nSenator Johnston and Senator\nNeely, Democrat, of West Virginia,\nhave been listed as two members\nof the District Committee who\nwould fight the sales tax.\nIncome Tax Exemptions.\nLikewise, Senator McGrath in\ndicated he did not believe it realis\ntic to expect Congress to apply the\ni city\u2019s income tax to all persons\nactually living here\u2014without the\ncomplete exemption of low income\ngroups as proposed in the pend\ning measure.\nThe House, it was recalled, twice\nhas rejected a plan in recent years\nbecause it would have meant ap\nplying the income levy to the\nWashington income of the \u201clittle j\nclerks\u201d working for the Govern-1\nment here but paying no District\ntax on the claim they are \u201cdomi\nciled\u201d in their home States rather\nthan here.\nUnder the present law, the city\nincome levy is applied to only\nabout 90,000 persons working\nhere, because the Government\nsalaries of all those claiming\n\"domicile\u2019* elsewhere are ex\nempted.\nFacing $2,500,000 deficit.\nSenator McGrath, who is chair\nman of the Democratic National\nCommittee, is \"deeply concerned\u201d\nover the state of city finance. The\nHouse slashed nearly $4,400,000\nfrom the Commissioners\u2019 \u201causter\nity\u201d budget^in the hope of stay\ning somewnere near balance,\nshould the revenue plan fail, but\nthis still left the 1950 budget un\nbalanced by more than $2,500,000.\nMembers of the congressional\ncommittees dealing with District;\nproblems noted that if Congress\ngrants retroactive pay raises to\ncity employes, to put them on a\npar with Federal workers, this\nwould add about $10,000,000 to\nthe deficit.\nPredictions also have been made\nthat the Senate would restore to\nthe budget many of the items\nslashed by the House.\nSenator McGrath said his in\ndorsement was general, that he\nwanted to study further some de\ntails of the sales tax plan. One\nquestion, he said, was whether\nradio and newspaper advertising\nshould be considered as a service\nor as a retail sale.\nRecent reports had it that the i\nJoint subcommittee had decided to\napply the retail sales tax to both\nnewspaper and radio advertising.\nOne question involved was whether\nthis would constitute double taxa\ntion since both the tax on adver\ntising for an article and its sale\nwould be expected to be passed\nalong to the consumer.\nSenator McGrath said he could\nsee some difficulties in this, es\npecially as to radio advertising\nsince much of it was interstate\nchain in character as against\nmerely local advertising. He saw\npossibilities of \u201cdiscrimination\" if\nonly local radio ads were taxed\nand nationally-advertised prod\nucts were exempted.\nSenate hearings on the District\u2019s\nbudget may be delayed for a time,\nbut not long, according to Senator\nHill, Democrat, of Alabama, head\nof the District Subcommittee of\nthe Senate Appropriations Com\nmittee. He said last night it was\nhis present intention to start open\npublic hearings \u201cwithin two\nweeks\u201d regardless of what action\nhas been taken meanwhile on the\nrevenue side of the picture.\nAs a first step, the District Com\nmissioners are to be asked to in\ndicate any changes they think\nshould be made in the spending\nbill as it passed the House.\nIran Bans Press Insults\nTo Shah, Foreign States\n1/ the Associated Press\nTEHERAN. Iran, Mar. 6.\u2014Thi\nMajlis (parliament) has passed a\nnew press law to slap down news\npapers which insult the Shah, hi*\nfamily or the heads of foreign\nstates.\nThe premier, members of hia\ncabinet, the speaker of the Maj\nlis and judges also are protected\nby the new measure, which pro\nvides for suppression of news\npapers which print insults against\nthem.\nThe writers of insulting articles,\nthe law says, must be arrested and\ndealt with in court within 24 hours\nafter their newspaper is sup\npressed.\nMussey Tent to Meet.\nEllen Spencer Mussey Tent No.\n1, Daughters of the Civil War, will\nmeet at its headquarters, 2015\nMassachusetts avenue N.W. tomor\nrow at 8 p.m.\nDOORS\nMany styles! Many sizes!\nRUCKER LUMRER\n1820 Wilson Blvd. Arl. CH. 0680\nLATEX FOAM\n(FOAM RUBBER) for Mottresses, Pillow*,\nFurniture, Boots, Cushions, Pods for Beds,\nAuto Seots, Etc. ANY QUANTITY,\nLatex Foam Products Co.\n807 H St. N.W,_ Sf. 3855\nWHAT ABOUT\nTHEIR FUTURE?,\nIt\u2019s the thoughtful man who provides for the\nfuture of his family. And now, while income\nis high, you can make this provision by saving\na regular proportion of your pay.\nYou can assure your children an education.\nYou can give vour family real security. You\ncan accumulate a cash balance to tide you over\na business slump. You can prepare against\ncontingencies with a savings account in\nTHE SECOND NATIONAL BANK\nWe welcome your savings account here at\nTHE SECOND NATIONAL, and remember,\nit\u2019s working for you every hour of every day\u2014\nEarning Interest!\nThe Second National\nBANK OF WASHINGTON\n\u201cAn Institution of Friendly Service**\n1333 G STREET N.W. REpublic 1700 509 SEVENTH ST. N.W.\nORGANIZED 1872\u2014RESOURCES OVER $30,000,000\nMEMBER FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\u2014MEMBER FEDERAL RESERVE SYSTEM","height":"31948","width":"22364"}}
